    "summary": "One of the most remarkable archaeological discoveries from Pre-Pottery Neolithic Jericho is the practice of plastered skull burial, dated to approximately 7500–6000 BCE. After death, the skull of the deceased was separated from the rest of the skeleton, and the face was reconstructed using plaster, with shells sometimes inserted into the eye sockets. The resulting objects, which bear individualized facial features, were apparently kept and displayed in domestic settings for extended periods before eventually being buried beneath the floors of houses.\n\nThe plastered skulls of Jericho are interpreted as evidence for an ancestor cult — a religious practice in which the spiritual presence or protective power of deceased community members was maintained through the preservation and display of their physical remains. Similar plastered skulls have been found at other Pre-Pottery Neolithic B sites across the Levant, including Ain Ghazal and Tell Ramad, indicating that this was a widespread cultural practice. These objects represent a sophisticated engagement with death, memory, and the relationship between the living and the dead that characterizes the symbolic world of early Neolithic communities.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jericho#Pre-Pottery_Neolithic",
